Successfully installed and configured Vercel Speed Insights for this React + Vite project.

## Changes Made

### 1. Installed Package
- Added `@vercel/speed-insights` (v2.0.0) to dependencies in package.json
- Updated package-lock.json with the new dependency and its 269 sub-packages

### 2. Configured SpeedInsights Component
Modified: `src/App.tsx`
- Added import: `import { SpeedInsights } from "@vercel/speed-insights/react"`
- Added the `<SpeedInsights />` component before the closing `</ErrorBoundary>` tag
- Positioned at the root level to track all routes and page views

## Implementation Details

Following the official Vercel Speed Insights documentation (fetched from https://vercel.com/docs/speed-insights/quickstart), I:

1. Identified this as a React + Vite project by examining:
   - vite.config.ts configuration file
   - package.json showing React 19.2.0 and Vite 7.3.1
   - Project structure with React components

2. Used the React/Vite specific installation instructions:
   - Installed the package using npm (the project's package manager)
   - Imported from `@vercel/speed-insights/react` (not Next.js or other framework variants)
   - Added component at the root app level for comprehensive tracking

3. Maintained existing code structure:
   - Preserved all existing imports and their order
   - Placed the SpeedInsights component at the end of the ErrorBoundary wrapper
   - No modifications to existing functionality

## Verification

✓ Build completed successfully with no errors
✓ TypeScript compilation passed
✓ Package installed and lockfile updated
✓ All changes staged in git

Note: Pre-existing linting warnings/errors in the codebase were not addressed as they are unrelated to this implementation.

## Next Steps

Once deployed to Vercel, the Speed Insights will automatically start collecting performance metrics. You can view the data in your Vercel dashboard under the Speed Insights section.
